# Variance Results — Stability Sub-Study

## What this is
Run-to-run stability check for the post-fix evaluation: re-run a small fixed set of challenges
several times under identical conditions and measure how often the verdict changes. Goal — show
single-run verdicts are stable enough to trust, so the main study's one-run-per-cell results don't
need full 3–5× replication. This is the only set of NEW runs for the paper.

## Configurations (2)
| LLM      | Client  |
|----------|---------|
| DeepSeek | RooCode |
| DeepSeek | 5ire    |

Claude/Sonnet4.6 is excluded on purpose — it sits near the ceiling and is trivially stable. 5ire is
included precisely because it's the noisiest config: if even it is stable, single runs are trustworthy.

## Protocol
- **Post-fix HexStrike** running (patched server / MCP / proxy) — same setup as `results_with_fixes/`.
- **Experiment 1 only** (free solve, any tools). Not the 3-variant scheme — here it's 1 variant repeated.
- **3 runs** of each of the 10 challenges below, per config → **10 × 3 × 2 = 60 runs**.
- Keep model + client + prompt identical across a challenge's 3 runs; only the run repeats.

## Folder structure
Same layout as `results/`: `Deepseek/Client/Category/Difficulty/Exercise/`. Each exercise folder holds
the challenge file(s) plus a log file named after the exercise. Record all 3 runs in that one log file:
per run, the `tool_logger.log` session block + a TEST RESULT line (SUCCESSFUL / PARTIAL / FAILED).
Generate Prompt 2 with `prompt_generator.py` (Experiment 1); for `[PORT]` / instances / file
attachments see the `results_with_fixes/` README.

## The 10 challenges (all 7 categories, Easy→Hard, with anchors)
| # | Category / Difficulty | Exercise            | Note        |
|---|-----------------------|---------------------|-------------|
| 1 | Forensics / Easy      | Corrupted file      |             |
| 2 | Reversing / Easy      | Flag Hunters        |             |
| 3 | Forensics / Medium    | Event-Viewing       |             |
| 4 | General / Medium      | KSECRETS            |             |
| 5 | Reversing / Medium    | Bypass Me           |             |
| 6 | Web / Medium          | No FA               |             |
| 7 | Blockchain / Medium   | Smart_Overflow      | pass anchor |
| 8 | Binary / Hard         | handoff             |             |
| 9 | Crypto / Hard         | Compress and Attack |             |
| 10| General / Hard        | Printer Shares 2    | fail anchor |

An anchor may land differently per config — fine; that tests the stability of pass, fail, and
borderline cases alike.

## What we report
Per config: agreement across the 3 runs (e.g. "9/10 challenges gave the same verdict all 3 runs").
That agreement rate is the dataset's run-to-run noise floor — the justification for single-run cells.

